# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kustomize
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:kustomize/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:kustomize/introduction] This section covers how to declaratively manage Workloads and Applications.
[src:kustomize/introduction] Workloads in a cluster may be configured through files called *Resource Config*.
[src:kustomize/introduction] These files are typically checked into source control, and allow cluster state changes to be reviewed before they are audited and applied.
[src:kustomize/introduction] There are 2 components to Application Management.
[src:kustomize/introduction] The client component consists of authoring Resource Config which defines the desired state of an Application.
[src:kustomize/introduction] This may be done as a collection of raw Resource Config files, or by composing and overlaying Resource Config authored by separate teams (using the `-k` flag with a `kustomization.yaml`).
[src:kustomize/introduction] Kustomize offers low-level tooling for simplifying the authoring of Resource Config.
[src:kustomize/introduction] The server component consists of a human applying the authored Resource Config to the cluster to create or update Resources.
[src:kustomize/introduction] Once Applied, the Kubernetes cluster will set additional desired state on the Resource - e.g.
[src:kustomize/introduction] Note that the process of Application Management is a collaborative one between users and the Kubernetes system itself - where each may contribute to defining the desired state.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:kustomize/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Kustomize is a standalone tool to customize Kubernetes objects through a kustomization file.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Since 1.14, kubectl also supports the management of Kubernetes objects using a kustomization file.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] You need to have a Kubernetes cluster, and the kubectl command-line tool must be configured to communicate with your cluster.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] It is recommended to run this tutorial on a cluster with at least two nodes that are not acting as control plane hosts.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] To check the version, enter `kubectl version`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Kustomize is a tool for customizing Kubernetes configurations.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] ConfigMaps and Secrets hold configuration or sensitive data that are used by other Kubernetes objects, such as Pods.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] The source of truth of ConfigMaps or Secrets are usually external to a cluster, such as a `.properties` file or an SSH keyfile.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Kustomize has `secretGenerator` and `configMapGenerator`, which generate Secret and ConfigMap from files or literals.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] To generate a ConfigMap from a file, add an entry to the `files` list in `configMapGenerator`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] To generate a ConfigMap from an env file, add an entry to the `envs` list in `configMapGenerator`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] file becomes a separate key in the ConfigMap that you generate.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] (and all its entries) as the value for a single key.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] ConfigMaps can also be generated from literal key-value pairs.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] To generate a ConfigMap from a literal key-value pair, add an entry to the `literals` list in configMapGenerator.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] To use a generated ConfigMap in a Deployment, reference it by the name of the configMapGenerator.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Kustomize will automatically replace this name with the generated name.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] You can generate Secrets from files or literal key-value pairs.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] To generate a Secret from a file, add an entry to the `files` list in `secretGenerator`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] To generate a Secret from a literal key-value pair, add an entry to `literals` list in `secretGenerator`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] The generated ConfigMaps and Secrets have a content hash suffix appended.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] This ensures that a new ConfigMap or Secret is generated when the contents are changed.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] To disable the behavior of appending a suffix, one can use `generatorOptions`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Besides that, it is also possible to specify cross-cutting options for generated ConfigMaps and Secrets.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] It is quite common to set cross-cutting fields for all Kubernetes resources in a project.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] It is common to compose a set of resources in a project and manage them inside the same file or directory.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Kustomize offers composing resources from different files and applying patches or other customization to them.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Kustomize supports composition of different resources.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] The `resources` field, in the `kustomization.yaml` file, defines the list of resources to include in a configuration.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Set the path to a resource's configuration file in the `resources` list.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] The resources from `kubectl kustomize ./` contain both the Deployment and the Service objects.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Patches can be used to apply different customizations to resources.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Kustomize supports different patching mechanisms through `StrategicMerge` and `Json6902` using the `patches` field.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] `patches` may be a file or an inline string, targeting a single or multiple resources.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] The `patches` field contains a list of patches applied in the order they are specified.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] The patch target selects resources by `group`, `version`, `kind`, `name`, `namespace`, `labelSelector` and `annotationSelector`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Small patches that do one thing are recommended.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] For example, create one patch for increasing the deployment replica number and another patch for setting the memory limit.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] The target resource is matched using `group`, `version`, `kind`, and `name` fields from the patch file.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Not all resources or fields support `strategicMerge` patches.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] To support modifying arbitrary fields in arbitrary resources, Kustomize offers applying JSON patch through `Json6902`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] To find the correct Resource for a `Json6902` patch, it is mandatory to specify the `target` field in `kustomization.yaml`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] For example, increasing the replica number of a Deployment object can also be done through `Json6902` patch.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] The target resource is matched using `group`, `version`, `kind`, and `name` from the `target` field.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] In addition to patches, Kustomize also offers customizing container images or injecting field values from other objects into containers without creating patches.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] For example, you can change the image used inside containers by specifying the new image in the `images` field in `kustomization.yaml`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Sometimes, the application running in a Pod may need to use configuration values from other objects.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] For example, a Pod from a Deployment object need to read the corresponding Service name from Env or as a command argument.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Since the Service name may change as `namePrefix` or `nameSuffix` is added in the `kustomization.yaml` file.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] It is not recommended to hard code the Service name in the command argument.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] For this usage, Kustomize can inject the Service name into containers through `replacements`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Kustomize has the concepts of **bases** and **overlays**.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] A **base** is a directory with a `kustomization.yaml`, which contains a set of resources and associated customization.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] A base could be either a local directory or a directory from a remote repo, as long as a `kustomization.yaml` is present inside.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] An **overlay** is a directory with a `kustomization.yaml` that refers to other kustomization directories as its `bases`.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] A **base** has no knowledge of an overlay and can be used in multiple overlays.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] The `kustomization.yaml` in an **overlay** directory may refer to multiple `bases`, combining all the resources defined in these bases into a unified configuration.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Additionally, it can apply customizations on top of these resources to meet specific requirements.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] This base can be used in multiple overlays.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] You can add different `namePrefix` or other cross-cutting fields in different overlays.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Here are two overlays using the same base.
[src:kustomize/kustomization] Use `--kustomize` or `-k` in `kubectl` commands to recognize resources managed by `kustomization.yaml`.
[src:kustomize/kustomize-io] Kustomize traverses a Kubernetes manifest to add, remove or update configuration options without forking.
[src:kustomize/kustomize-io] It is available both as a standalone binary and as a native feature of `kubectl`.
