[src:kustomize/yaml] Custom data types are allowed, but YAML natively encodes scalars (such as strings, integers, and floats), lists, and associative arrays (also known as maps, dictionaries or hashmaps).
[src:kustomize/yaml] These data types are based on the Perl programming language, though all commonly used high-level programming languages share very similar concepts.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The colon-centered syntax, used for expressing key-value pairs, is inspired by electronic mail headers as defined in RFC 822, and the document separator `---` is borrowed from MIME (RFC 2046).
[src:kustomize/yaml] Escape sequences are reused from C, and whitespace wrapping for multi-line strings is inspired by HTML.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Lists and hashes can contain nested lists and hashes, forming a tree structure; arbitrary graphs can be represented using YAML aliases (similar to XML in SOAP).
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML is intended to be read and written in streams, a feature inspired by SAX.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Support for reading and writing YAML is available for many programming languages.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Some source-code editors such as Vim, Emacs, and various integrated development environments have features that make editing YAML easier, such as folding up nested structures or automatically highlighting syntax errors.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The official recommended filename extension for YAML files has been `.yaml` since 2006.
[src:kustomize/yaml] In 2024, the MIME type `application/yaml` has been finalized.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML (/ˈjæməl/, rhymes with *camel*) was first proposed by Clark Evans in 2001, who designed it together with Ingy döt Net and Oren Ben-Kiki.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Originally YAML was said to mean *Yet Another Markup Language*, because it was released in an era that saw a proliferation of markup languages for presentation and connectivity (HTML, XML, SGML, etc.).
[src:kustomize/yaml] A cheat sheet and full specification are available at the official site.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The following is a synopsis of the basic elements.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML accepts the entire Unicode character set, except for some control characters, and may be encoded in any one of UTF-8, UTF-16 or UTF-32.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Conventional block format uses a hyphen+space to begin a new item in list.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Optional inline format is delimited by comma+space and enclosed in brackets (similar to JSON).
[src:kustomize/yaml] Keys are separated from values by a colon+space.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Indented blocks, common in YAML data files, use indentation and new lines to separate the key/value pairs.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Inline blocks, common in YAML data streams, use comma+space to separate the key/value pairs between braces.
[src:kustomize/yaml] There are two ways to write multi-line strings, one preserving newlines (using the `|` character) and one that folds the newlines (using the `>` character), both followed by a newline character.
[src:kustomize/yaml] By default, the leading indentation (of the first line) and trailing whitespace are stripped, though other behavior can be explicitly specified.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Folded text converts newlines to spaces and removes leading whitespace.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Objects and lists are important components in yaml and can be mixed.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The first example is a list of key-value objects, all people from the Smith family.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The second lists them by gender; it is a key-value object containing two lists.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Features that distinguish YAML from the capabilities of other data-serialization languages are structures, and data and composite keys.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML structures enable storage of multiple documents within a single file, usage of references for repeated nodes, and usage of arbitrary nodes as keys.
[src:kustomize/yaml] For clarity, compactness, and avoiding data entry errors, YAML provides node anchors (using `&`) and references (using `*`).
[src:kustomize/yaml] References to the anchor work for all data types (see the ship-to reference in the example below).
[src:kustomize/yaml] Below is an example of a queue in an instrument sequencer in which two steps are referenced without being fully described.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Explicit data typing is seldom seen in the majority of YAML documents since YAML autodetects simple types.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Data types can be divided into three categories: core, defined, and user-defined.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Core are ones expected to exist in any parser (e.g. floats, ints, strings, lists, maps, ...).
[src:kustomize/yaml] Many more advanced data types, such as binary data, are defined in the YAML specification but not supported in all implementations.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Finally YAML defines a way to extend the data type definitions locally to accommodate user-defined classes, structures or primitives (e.g. quad-precision floats).
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML autodetects the datatype of the entity, but sometimes one wants to cast the datatype explicitly.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The most common situation is where a single-word string that looks like a number, Boolean or tag requires disambiguation by surrounding it with quotes or using an explicit datatype tag.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Not every implementation of YAML has every specification-defined data type.
[src:kustomize/yaml] These built-in types use a double-exclamation sigil prefix (`!!`).
[src:kustomize/yaml] Particularly interesting ones not shown here are sets, ordered maps, timestamps, and hexadecimal.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Here is an example of base64-encoded binary data.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Many implementations of YAML can support user-defined data types for object serialization.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Local data types are not universal data types but are defined in the application using the YAML parser library.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Local data types use a single exclamation mark (`!`).
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML supports composite keys, which consist of multiple values.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Such keys are useful for coordinate transformations, multi-field identifiers, test cases with compound conditions, and the like.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Data-structure hierarchy is maintained by outline indentation.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Notice that strings do not require enclosure in quotation marks.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The specific number of spaces in the indentation is unimportant as long as parallel elements have the same left justification and the hierarchically nested elements are indented further.
[src:kustomize/yaml] This sample document defines an associative array with 7 top level keys: one of the keys, "items", contains a 2-element list, each element of which is itself an associative array with differing keys.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Relational data and redundancy removal are displayed: the "ship-to" associative array content is copied from the "bill-to" associative array's content as indicated by the anchor (`&`) and reference (`*`) labels.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Optional blank lines can be added for readability.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Multiple documents can exist in a single file/stream and are separated by `---`.
[src:kustomize/yaml] An optional `...` can be used at the end of a file (useful for signaling an end in streamed communications without closing the pipe).
[src:kustomize/yaml] Because YAML primarily relies on outline indentation for structure, it is especially resistant to delimiter collision.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML may be placed in JSON by quoting and escaping all interior quotation marks.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML may be placed in XML by escaping reserved characters (`<`, `>`, `&`, `'`, `"`) and converting whitespace, or by placing it in a CDATA section.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Unlike JSON, which can only represent data in a hierarchical model with each child node having a single parent, YAML also offers a simple relational scheme that allows repeats of identical data to be referenced from two or more points in the tree rather than entered redundantly at those points.
[src:kustomize/yaml] This is similar to the facility IDREF built into XML.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The YAML parser then expands these references into the fully populated data structures they imply when read in, so whatever program is using the parser does not have to be aware of a relational encoding model, unlike XML processors, which do not expand references.
[src:kustomize/yaml] This expansion can enhance readability while reducing data entry errors in configuration files or processing protocols where many parameters remain the same in a sequential series of records while only a few vary.
[src:kustomize/yaml] An example being that "ship-to" and "bill-to" records in an invoice are nearly always the same data.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML is purely a data-representation language and thus has no executable commands.
[src:kustomize/yaml] While validation and safe parsing is inherently possible in any data language, implementation is such a notorious pitfall that YAML's lack of an associated command language may be a relative security benefit.
[src:kustomize/yaml] However, YAML allows language-specific tags so that arbitrary local objects can be created by a parser that supports those tags.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Any YAML parser that allows sophisticated object instantiation to be executed opens the potential for an injection attack.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Perl parsers that allow loading of objects of arbitrary classes create so-called "blessed" values.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Using these values may trigger unexpected behavior, e.g. if the class uses overloaded operators.
[src:kustomize/yaml] This may lead to execution of arbitrary Perl code.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The situation is similar for Python or Ruby parsers.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The YAML specification identifies an *instance document* as a "Presentation" or "character stream".
[src:kustomize/yaml] The primary logical structures in a YAML instance document are scalars, sequences, and mappings.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The YAML specification also indicates some basic constraints that apply to these primary logical structures.
[src:kustomize/yaml] For example, according to the specification, mapping keys do not have an order.
[src:kustomize/yaml] In every case where node order is significant, a sequence must be used.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Moreover, in defining conformance for YAML processors, the YAML specification defines two primary operations: *dump* and *load*.
[src:kustomize/yaml] All YAML-compliant processors must provide *at least* one of these operations, and may optionally provide both.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Finally, the YAML specification defines an *information model* or "representation graph", which must be created during processing for both *dump* and *load* operations, although this representation need not be made available to the user through an API.
[src:kustomize/yaml] JSON syntax is a basis of YAML version 1.2, which was promulgated with the express purpose of bringing YAML "into compliance with JSON as an official subset".
[src:kustomize/yaml] Though prior versions of YAML were not strictly compatible, the discrepancies were rarely noticeable, and most JSON documents can be parsed by some YAML parsers such as Syck.
[src:kustomize/yaml] This is because JSON's semantic structure is equivalent to the optional "inline-style" of writing YAML.
[src:kustomize/yaml] While extended hierarchies can be written in inline-style like JSON, this is not a recommended YAML style except when it aids clarity.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML has many additional features not present in JSON, including comments, extensible data types, relational anchors, strings without quotation marks, and mapping types preserving key order.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Due to the conciseness, JSON serialization and deserialization is much faster than YAML.
[src:kustomize/yaml] TOML was designed to be an advancement of the .ini file format.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML makes minimal use of indicator characters compared to TOML's strict requirement of quotation marks and square brackets.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML's use of significant indentation has been contrasted with the dot notation of TOML's key and table names to convey the same semantic structure.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Opinions differ on which convention leads to more-readable configuration files.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML lacks the notion of tag attributes that are found in XML.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Instead YAML has extensible type declarations (including class types for objects).
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML itself does not have XML's language-defined document schema descriptors that allow, for example, a document to self-validate.
[src:kustomize/yaml] However, there are several externally defined schema descriptor languages for YAML (e.g.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Doctrine, Kwalify and Rx) that fulfill that role.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Moreover, the semantics provided by YAML's language-defined type declarations in the YAML document itself frequently relaxes the need for a validator in simple, common situations.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Additionally, YAXML, which represents YAML data structures in XML, allows XML schema importers and output mechanisms like XSLT to be applied to YAML.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Comparison of data-serialization formats provides a more comprehensive comparison of YAML with other serialization formats.
[src:kustomize/yaml] For fixed data structures, YAML files can simply be generated using *print* commands that write both the data and the YAML specific decoration.
[src:kustomize/yaml] To dump varying, or complex, hierarchical data, however, a dedicated YAML *emitter* is preferable.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Similarly, simple YAML files (e.g. key-value pairs) are readily parsed with regular expressions.
[src:kustomize/yaml] For more complex, or varying, data structures, a formal YAML *parser* is recommended.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML emitters and parsers exist for many popular languages.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Most of them are written in the native language itself.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Some are language bindings of the C library *libyaml*; they may run faster.
[src:kustomize/yaml] There used to be another C library, called *Syck*, written and orphaned by why the lucky stiff: it is unmaintained, there is no authoritative source bundle, and the web site has been hijacked.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Hence the only recommendable C library is *libyaml*.
[src:kustomize/yaml] It was originally developed by Kirill Simonov.
[src:kustomize/yaml] In 2018, development was resumed by the new maintainers Ian Cordasco and Ingy döt Net.
[src:kustomize/yaml] C++ programmers have the choice between the C library *libyaml* and the C++ library *libyaml-cpp*.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Both have completely independent code bases and completely different APIs.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The library *libyaml-cpp* still has a major version number of 0, indicating that the API may change at any moment, as happened indeed after version 0.3.
[src:kustomize/yaml] There is a grammar-focused implementation written in C#, with an aim on extensions for the nested elements.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Some implementations of YAML, such as Perl's YAML.pm, will load an entire file (stream) and parse it *en masse*.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Other implementations like PyYaml are lazy and iterate over the next document only upon request.
[src:kustomize/yaml] For very large files in which one plans to handle the documents independently, instantiating the entire file before processing may be prohibitive.
[src:kustomize/yaml] Thus in YAML.pm, occasionally one must chunk a file into documents and parse those individually.
[src:kustomize/yaml] YAML makes this easy, since this simply requires splitting on the document end marker, which is defined as three periods at the start of a line followed by a whitespace (and possible a comment).
[src:kustomize/yaml] In static, compiled languages, this instantiation is complex to achieve and is quite often not implemented.
[src:kustomize/yaml] The perceived flaws and complexity of YAML has led to the emergence of stricter alternatives such as StrictYAML and NestedText.
